gap in our knowledge of immigration to Argentina, one of the world's primary "settler" societies. Moya moves deftly between micro- and macro-analysis to illuminate the immigration phenomenon. A wealth of primary sources culled from dozens of immigrant associations, national and village archives, and interviews with surviving participants in Argentina and Spain inform his discussion of the origins of Spanish immigration, residence patterns, community formation, labor, and cultural cognitive aspects of the immigration process. In addition, he provides valuable material on other immigrant groups in Argentina and gives a balanced critique of major issues in migration studies.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImmigrantsxHistoryxArgentinaxBuenos Aires. 0aImmigrantszArgentinazBuenos AiresxHistory. 0aSocial adjustmentxArgentinaxBuenos Aires. 0aSocial adjustmentzArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aSocial adjustmentzArgentina. 0aSpaniardsxCultural assimilationxArgentinaxBuenos Aires. 0aSpaniardsxCultural assimilationzArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aSpaniardsxHistoryxArgentinaxBuenos Aires. 0aSpaniardszArgentinazBuenos AiresxHistory. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 4aLatin America. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh1 aMoya, Jose C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092153540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520921535423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520921535/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles